Question: file comparison with memory consideration: :I want to compare two files, one is in file system and the other is being downloaded from a HTTP URL. We have tried to compare by byte[] arrays (we used HTTPRequestBuilder by Apache), but the concern is that the files may be too large and they may exhaust the memory. Do we have any good alternates.
Please using this api: InputStream.read.
Answer:<<<api>>>: InputStream.read
<<<code>>>: 
InputStream inputStream1 = new FileInputStream(file1);
InputStream inputStream2 = new URL(url).openStream();
byte[] buffer1 = new byte[1024];
byte[] buffer2 = new byte[1024];
int bytesRead1;
int bytesRead2;
while ((bytesRead1 = inputStream1.read(buffer1)) != -1 && (bytesRead2 = inputStream2.read(buffer2)) != -1) {
    if (!Arrays.equals(buffer1, buffer2)) {
        // Files are not equal
        break;
    }
}
<<<explanation>>>: The read() method of the InputStream class reads the next byte of data from the input stream. It returns the total number of bytes read into the buffer, or -1 if there is no more data because the end of the stream has been reached. This is a good way to compare the contents of two files without loading the entire file into memory.
